import os, shutil, pathlib

original_dir = pathlib.Path((r"C:\Users\ponnu\Downloads\catsndogs\Data\train\train"))
new_base_dir = pathlib.Path("../data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats_small")

def make_subset(subset_name, start_index, end_index):
    for category in ("cat", "dog"):
        dir = new_base_dir / subset_name / category
        os.makedirs(dir)
        fnames = [f"{category}.{i}.jpg" for i in range(start_index, end_index)]
        for fname in fnames:
            shutil.copyfile(src=original_dir / fname,
                            dst=dir / fname)

make_subset("train", start_index=0, end_index=1000)       # 1,000 images (500 cats + 500 dogs)
make_subset("validation", start_index=1000, end_index=1500)  # 500 images (250 cats + 250 dogs)
make_subset("test", start_index=1500, end_index=2500)        # 1,000 images (500 cats + 500 dogs)

  • Define the first model
In [98]:
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(180, 180, 3))
x = layers.Rescaling(1./255)(inputs)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.Flatten()(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)
model = keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)


model.compile(loss="binary_crossentropy",
              optimizer="rmsprop",
              metrics=["accuracy", "Precision", "Recall"])

    epochs=15,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=callbacks)

  • Explore the perfromance metrics
In [102]:
# Initialize empty lists to store true labels and predicted probabilities
y_true = []
y_pred_prob = []

# Iterate over the test dataset to collect true labels and predicted probabilities
for images, labels in test_dataset:
    # Append true labels directly to the list 
    y_true.append(labels.numpy())  
    y_pred_prob_batch = test_model.predict(images)
    y_pred_prob.append(y_pred_prob_batch)

y_true = np.concatenate(y_true, axis=0)  # Concatenate all true labels from the batches
y_pred_prob = np.concatenate(y_pred_prob, axis=0)  # Concatenate all predicted probabilities from the batches

# Convert probabilities to binary predictions (threshold = 0.5)
y_pred = (y_pred_prob > 0.5).astype(int)  # Convert probabilities to binary class predictions

# Compute Precision, Recall, and F1-Score
precision = precision_score(y_true, y_pred)
recall = recall_score(y_true, y_pred)
f1 = f1_score(y_true, y_pred)

# Print the results
print(f"Precision: {precision:.4f}")
print(f"Recall: {recall:.4f}")
print(f"F1-Score: {f1:.4f}")

# Load VGG16 pre-trained on ImageNet
base_model = keras.applications.vgg16.VGG16(
    weights="imagenet",
    include_top=False,
    input_shape=(180, 180, 3)
)

# Freeze the base layers of VGG16
base_model.trainable = False

## extracting features from the pre-trained VGG16 model

def get_features_and_labels(dataset):
    all_features = []
    all_labels = []
    for images, labels in dataset:
        preprocessed_images = keras.applications.vgg16.preprocess_input(images)
        features = base_model.predict(preprocessed_images)   
        all_features.append(features)   
        all_labels.append(labels)
    return np.concatenate(all_features), np.concatenate(all_labels)

train_features, train_labels =  get_features_and_labels(train_dataset)
val_features, val_labels =  get_features_and_labels(validation_dataset)
test_features, test_labels =  get_features_and_labels(test_dataset)

In [110]:
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Flatten, Dense, Dropout

model1 = keras.Sequential([
    keras.layers.Input(shape=(5, 5, 512)),  # Match the shape of your features
    Flatten(),                              # Flatten the 4D features to 1D
    Dense(256, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.5),
    Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')          # Binary classification
])

# Compile the model
model1.compile(loss="binary_crossentropy", 
              optimizer="rmsprop", 
              metrics=["accuracy", "Precision", "Recall"])

# Define callbacks to monitor overfitting and save the best model
callbacks = [
    ModelCheckpoint(
        filepath="./models/feature_extraction.keras", 
        save_best_only=True, 
        monitor="val_loss"),  # Save only the best model based on val_loss
]

# Train the model with the extracted features
history = model1.fit(
    train_features, train_labels,
    epochs=10,
    validation_data=(val_features, val_labels),
    callbacks=callbacks  # Include callbacks to track overfitting
)

Conclusion¶

  1. First Model Performance:

  • Precision: 0.7449

  • Recall: 0.6950

  • F1-Score: 0.7191

Confusion Matrix:

  • True Negatives (TN): 762

  • False Positives (FP): 238

  • False Negatives (FN): 305

  • True Positives (TP): 695

Precision-Recall AUC: 0.8033

Test Loss: 0.5491

Test Accuracy: 0.7285

The first model shows reasonable performance with a balanced recall and precision, but there is room for improvement. The relatively high number of false positives (238) suggests that the model may be classifying some cats as dogs, which could indicate a bias toward the positive class (dog) and lower precision. The Precision-Recall AUC of 0.8033 indicates the model has a fair ability to discriminate between the classes.

  1. Second Model Performance:

  • Precision: 0.9846

  • Recall: 0.9560

  • F1-Score: 0.9701

Confusion Matrix:

  • True Negatives (TN): 985

  • False Positives (FP): 15

  • False Negatives (FN): 44

  • True Positives (TP): 956

Precision-Recall AUC: 0.9927

Test Loss: 0.4849

Test Accuracy: 0.9705

The second model, which uses VGG16 for feature extraction, performs significantly better than the first model, with notably higher precision, recall, and F1-score. The confusion matrix shows very few false positives and false negatives, indicating excellent performance in distinguishing between cats and dogs. The Precision-Recall AUC of 0.9927 reflects outstanding balance and overall classification ability.
